N PART" subdoc="false" toc-caption="PART 7  PARTIES TO PROCEEDINGS AND REPRESENTATION [rr 7.1&#x2013;7.42]"><leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT7.D3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="division" searchtype="LEGISLATION DIVISION" subdoc="false" toc-caption="DIVISION 3  EXECUTORS, ADMINISTRATORS AND TRUSTEES [rr 7.11, 7.12]">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading><desig searchtype="DIV-NUM"><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT7.D3" type="ext"/>DIVISION 3</designum></desig><title searchtype="DIV-TITLE"> EXECUTORS, ADMINISTRATORS AND TRUSTEES [rr 7.11, 7.12]</title></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-11"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 7.11] r 7.11 Executors, administrators and trustees (cf SCR Part 68, rule 4)">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-11" type="ext"/>[r 7.11]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Executors, administrators and trustees (cf SCR Part 68, rule 4)</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>7.11</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-11.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-11.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>In proceedings relating to an estate, all executors of the will of the deceased, or all administrators of the estate, must be parties unless one or more of them has represented the others pursuant to rule 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-4" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"> rule 7.4</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
.</text></p>
<leg:histnote>
<p><text>[subr (1)  am Gaz 116 of 7 September 2007  r 2 and Sch 1[3], effective 7 September 2007]</text></p></leg:histnote>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-11.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-11.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>In proceedings relating to a trust, all trustees must be parties.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-11.3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-11.3" type="ext"/>(3)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>In proceedings commenced by executors, administrators or trustees, any executor, administrator or trustee who does not consent to being joined as a plaintiff must be made a defendant.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-12"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 7.12] r 7.12 Beneficiaries and claimants (cf SCR Part 68, rule 5)">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-12" type="ext"/>[r 7.12]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Beneficiaries and claimants (cf SCR Part 68, rule 5)</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>7.12</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-12.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-12.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>In proceedings relating to an estate, all persons having a beneficial interest in or claim against the estate need not be parties, but the plaintiff may make parties of such of those persons as he or she thinks fit.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-12.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-12.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>In proceedings relating to a trust, all persons having a beneficial interest under the trust need not be parties, but the plaintiff may make parties of such of those persons as he or she thinks fit.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-12.3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-12.3" type="ext"/>(3)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>This rule has effect despite
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R6-20" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"> rule 6.20</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 (Proceedings affecting persons having joint entitlement).</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:bodytext>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTES"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT7.R12.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTES</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.7-12-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[7.12.5] Joinder of interested persons">
<glp:note><blockquote><hrule/>
<p>
<text><inlineobject attachment="web-server" filename="leg1.gif" type="image"/> Legislation cited in [7.12.5] below. LawNow subscribers click through for daily updates and historical versions.</text><text> </text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_REG_2005-418" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Uniform Civil Procedure Rules 2005</remotelink> r 7.6.</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
</p></blockquote></glp:note><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.7-12-5" type="ext"/>[7.12.5] </edpnum><title>Joinder of interested persons</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>The appropriateness of joining potentially affected beneficiaries and claimants will usually depend on the extent to which their interests are likely to be adequately represented by the active parties in the proceedings. (If there are numerous persons constituting a class, or a class includes unidentified or unborn persons, a representative order should be sought: see 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R7-6" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">r 7.6</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
.) As a general rule, executors and trustees, subject to their general obligation to argue for the benefit and protection of the will or estate (as the case may be), should not argue for the interests of any particular beneficiary: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr001412" spanref="cr001412-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WN"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1901"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="202"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Burton</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001412-001" status="unval">[1901] WN 202</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="214240" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. However, this does not preclude an objective presentation of the arguments capable of being presented in the interests of potential beneficiaries and claimants, especially where no order has been made for their separate representation. Where the potentially affected persons are joined, the usual procedure is for the plaintiff to inform the various classes of defendants that the members of a class should retain the same solicitor and counsel &#x2014; in order to minimise the costs of the proceedings and the potential burden on the estate.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.7-12-10" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[7.12.10] Costs of proceedings"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.7-12-10" type="ext"/>[7.12.10] </edpnum><title>Costs of proceedings</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Normally the costs of the plaintiff and the defendants will be ordered to be paid out of the fund in dispute as long as the point involved would have appeared to competent counsel to have been fairly arguable: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr001413" spanref="cr001413-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WAR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1963"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="36"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref anaphref="cr001413" spanref="cr001413-002" status="unval"><ci:pinpoint num="50" targettype="page"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Elders Trustee &amp; Executor Co Ltd v Eastoe</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001413-001" status="unval">[1963] WAR 36</ci:span> <ci:span spanid="cr001413-002" status="unval">at 50</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="123647" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Where a trustee properly seeks construction of the trust instrument, the rule to be departed from only in exceptional cases is that the costs are payable out of the residuary estate: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1964"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr001414" spanref="cr001414-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="CLR"/><ci:volume num="112"/><ci:page num="52"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr001415" spanref="cr001415-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1964"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="1100"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Pohlner v Pfeiffer</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001414-001" status="unval">(1964) 112 CLR 52</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr001415-002" status="unval">[1964] ALR 1100</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="44435" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr001416" spanref="cr001416-001"><ci:reporter value="VR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1969"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="545"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Mulcahy</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001416-001">[1969] VR 545</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="101490" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. If, however, despite their form the proceedings are really adversary litigation between the beneficiaries, the unsuccessful party should pay the costs: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr001417" spanref="cr001417-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="Ch"/><ci:volume num="1"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1912"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="435"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Halston</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001417-001" status="unval">[1912] 1 Ch 435</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="31530" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1914"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr001418" spanref="cr001418-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WNNSW"/><ci:volume num="31"/><ci:page num="44"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Cunningham</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001418-001" status="unval">(1914) 31 WN (NSW) 44</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="181310" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1931"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr001419" spanref="cr001419-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WNNSW"/><ci:volume num="48"/><ci:page num="85"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">O'Brien v Ritchie</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001419-001" status="unval">(1931) 48 WN (NSW) 85</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="67824" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr001420" spanref="cr001420-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WAR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1963"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="36"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Elders Trustee &amp; Executor Co Ltd v Eastoe</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr001420-001" status="unval">[1963] WAR 36</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="123647" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
</bodytext>
